    <p>
      6. What do you notice about the values of <m>(\frac{C}{d})</m>?
    </p>
    <p>
      Connect.
    </p>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The circumference is the distance round a circle.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            When you divide the circumference by the diameter of any circular object, the number you get is 
            approximately <m>3.14</m> correct to two decimal places.
            <me>
              \frac{Circumference}{diameter} = 3.14
            </me>            
          </p>
          <p>
            Circumference <m>= 3.14 \times\text {diameter}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The number <m>3.14</m> is called <m>\textbf {pi}</m> and is represented by the symbol <m>\pi</m>. As a fraction, <m>\pi = \frac {22}{7}</m>.
            Therefore, circumference <m> = \pi d</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Two radii are equal to the diameter. Hence <m>d = 2r</m>            
          </p>
          <p>
            Circumference 
            <md>
              <mrow>= \amp  \pi \times d</mrow>
              <mrow>= \amp \pi \times 2r</mrow>
              <mrow>= \amp 2\pi r </mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </activity>


  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The diameter of a circle is <m>21\, cm</m>. Find its circumference.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Circumference <m>= \pi D</m> where <m>D</m> is the diameter of a circle.
      </p>
      <p>
        Therefore,
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow> \text{Circumference} =\amp (\frac{22}{7} \times 21)cm </mrow>
          <mrow> =\amp 66\, cm </mrow>
          
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        The circumference<m>= {\color{blue} 66\,cm}</m>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
